IBM Applied Data Science Capstone¶

Where to Open LA's Next Artisanal Coffee Shop?¶

Christian Akira McKinnon¶

Introduction / Executive Summary:¶

According to Statista, Los Angeles was ranked only 5th, in the US, in terms of having the largest number of Starbucks Coffeehouses, trailing cities like New York and Chicago. There are numerous possible explanations as to why, however the rise of the craft coffee movement is most certainly one of them. A growing awareness of concerns surrounding ESG (Environmental, Social and Corporate Governance), sustainability and sourcing has converted directly into consumers' daily purchasing habits.

Artisanal Coffee shops like "Upside Down" in Westwood have taken these concerns into account by sourcing their coffee from global producers with sustainable and ethical production practices. Despite higher costs, consumer demand has remained remarkably resilient as many consumers feel sustainable sourcing justifies the expensive cost.

LA has long been a trendsetter in terms of embracing fringe industries that since become mainstream, and artisanal coffee shops are no exception. Prospective entrepreneurs and investors alike are constantly scouring new opportunities to build profitable businesses in the right locations, but how exactly are these decisions made and what kind of data is used to inform these decisions?

In this report, we will scrape publicly available real-world data, and perform any required tidying before integrating it with geocoding services and the FourSquare API. Our analysis will be driven by visualizations including barplots and heatmaps, as well as statistical metrics such as correlation and averages to better refine our understanding and make predictions. K-means clustering will then be applied to FourSquare venues in LA neighborhoods to determine where best to open LA's next artisanal coffee shop.

Data Sources:¶

In the following report, we will analyze data from the following sources to determine where best to open Los Angeles's next craft coffee shop:

1.) The Foursquare API in order to locate and list different venues such as cafes, restaurants, shops and other services in order to better refine prospective neighborhoods.

2.) The GeoPy Nominatim Libary in order to locate the coordinates of all venues and neighborhoods.

3.) The Wikipedia Entry for the List of districts and neighborhoods in Los Angeles. In the following report, we will analyze data from the following sources to determine where best to open Los Angeles's next craft coffee shop:

1.) The Foursquare API in order to locate and list different venues such as cafes, restaurants, shops and other services in order to better refine prospective neighborhoods. It will also be the source of venue-based features in our dataframe including "Venues" and "Venue Category."

2.) The GeoPy Nominatim Libary in order to locate the coordinates of all venues and neighborhoods. It will provide the "Latitude" and "Longitude" features in our dataframe.

3.) The Wikipedia Entry for the List of districts and neighborhoods in Los Angeles will provide the data for our "Neighborhood" feature.

4.) Average Monthly Rental Data scraped from the rental platform RENTCafe, a US-based rental listing service for landlords and tenants. It maintains up-to-date listings of apartments for rent as well as data to determine the average cost of certain districts and neighborhoods. It will provide our values for the "Average Rent" feature in our dataframe.

Methodology:¶

We will begin by installing or loading any required libaries or packages and detail their purposes.

In order to determine ideal locations for new high-end coffee shops, we will first scrape the Wikipedia HTML data for LA neighborhoods and clean any NAs or correct any strings (such as duplicates) that require tidying.

The GeoPy Nominatim Geolocator library will then be used to find the coordinates of LA and its neighborhoods. It will then be applied in conjunction with the Folium library to map out our data visually.

Next, the data will be fed through the FourSquare API from where we can begin our exploratory data analysis (EDA) by creating visualizations including scatterplots and treemaps to better convey correlations between the variables.

Our EDA will parse and collate neighborhood venue data in order to create visual rankings and potential predictions about neighborhoods that are likely to welcome a new artisanal coffee shop.

The average LA Monthly Rental Data from RENTCafe will then be scraped and joined with our main dataframe to determine whether any correlation between the number of coffee venues and the average monthly rental price exists.

After completing our EDA and establishing a better understanding of the data, we will apply the popular K-Means Clustering machine-learning algorithm to the dataset to define a range of desirable clusters from which we can base our preliminary recommendations.

In [20]:
# define a loop using Nominatim to populate the dataframe
for i in range(0, len(df)):
    address = df.Neighborhood[i] + ', Los Angeles, CA'
    location = geolocator.geocode(address)
    if location == None:
        latitude = 'NA'
        longitude = 'NA'
    else:
        latitude = location.latitude
        longitude = location.longitude

    neighborhoods = neighborhoods.append({'Neighborhood': df.Neighborhood[i],
                                              'Latitude': latitude,
                                              'Longitude': longitude}, ignore_index = True)

In [29]:
# Use the function provided in the lab to get the LA venues for every neighborhood in our "neighborhoods" df.
def getNearbyVenues(names, latitudes, longitudes, radius = 500):
    
    venues_list=[]
    for name, lat, lng in zip(names, latitudes, longitudes):
        print(name)
            
        # create the API request URL
        url3 = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/explore?&client_id={}&client_secret={}&v={}&ll={},{}&radius={}&limit={}'.format(
            CLIENT_ID, 
            CLIENT_SECRET, 
            VERSION, 
            lat, 
            lng, 
            radius, 
            LIMIT)
            
        # make the GET request
        results = requests.get(url3).json()["response"]['groups'][0]['items']
        
        # return only relevant information for each nearby venue
        venues_list.append([(
            name, 
            lat, 
            lng,
            v['venue']['name'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lat'], 
            v['venue']['location']['lng'],  
            v['venue']['categories'][0]['name']) for v in results])

    nearby_venues = pd.DataFrame([item for venue_list in venues_list for item in venue_list])
    nearby_venues.columns = ['Neighborhood', 
                  'Neighborhood Latitude', 
                  'Neighborhood Longitude', 
                  'Venue', 
                  'Venue Latitude', 
                  'Venue Longitude', 
                  'Venue Category']
    
    return(nearby_venues)

Due to the fact that there are an enormous number of unique categories, we will break these down into the parent and child dictionaries as provided through the Foursquare venue search option.

In [33]:
# New url specifically for venues
url4 = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/categories'
params = {
    "client_id": CLIENT_ID,
    "client_secret": CLIENT_SECRET,
    "v": VERSION,
}

gencat = {} # Create the parent & child dictionary titled "gencat"

# We will define a function to access the general vs specific venue categories
def cat_access(cat, prev):
    if cat.get('categories', False):
        lvl = len(prev) - 1
        for vencat in cat['categories']:
            child = vencat['name']
            cat_access(vencat, prev + [child])
            
            if child not in gencat:
                gencat[child] = [(prev[0], 0)]
                
            for i in range(1, lvl + 1):
                gencat[child].append((prev[i], i))
In [34]:

In [35]:

    name = cat['name']
    cat_access(cat, [name])

Target: Coffee Shops¶

The aim of our process is to identify suitable neighorhoods to open an artisanal coffee shop. As such, we will begin by first noting the different types of venues in which coffee is traditionally served. These instances in our dataframe include "Coffee Shop," "Cafe," (along with the alternative convention "Café" placing a diacritic mark over the e). Restaurants are also likely to serve coffee, however due to the wide scope of dishes served, we will not include them in this part of our analysis. We will also remove "Cafeteria" as they are self-serve restaurants, not coffee shops.

In [52]:
# Filter out new df "la_cafe" for the keywords above while removing "Cafeteria"
selected_cols = ['Venue' or 'Venue Category']
la_cafe = la_venues_final.loc[~la_venues_final[selected_cols].apply(lambda x: x.str.contains('Cafeteria')).all(axis=1)]
la_cafe = la_cafe[la_cafe[selected_cols].apply(lambda x: x.str.contains('Café|Cafe|Coffee')).all(axis=1)]

In [72]:
# define a function to sort values by descending order
def return_most_common_venues(row, num_top_venues):
    row_categories = row.iloc[1:]
    row_categories_sorted = row_categories.sort_values(ascending=False)
    
    return row_categories_sorted.index.values[0:num_top_venues]
In [73]:
# assign a vector for the top 5 venues
num_top_venues = 5

indicators = ['st', 'nd', 'rd']

# create columns according to number of top venues
columns = ['Neighborhood']
for ind in np.arange(num_top_venues):
    try:
        columns.append('{}{} Most Common Venue'.format(ind+1, indicators[ind]))
    except:
        columns.append('{}th Most Common Venue'.format(ind+1))

# create a new dataframe
la_ven_sorted = pd.DataFrame(columns=columns)

for ind in np.arange(la_grouped_mean.shape[0]):
    la_ven_sorted.iloc[ind, 1:] = return_most_common_venues(la_grouped_mean.iloc[ind, :], num_top_venues)

Modeling: K-Means Clustering¶

This unsupervised and iterative machine-learning algorithm is often applied to messy real-world data such as consumer data for market segmentation and geospatial data for location-based analysis. It parses datasets with numerous observations into k clusters based on a centroid or simply a cluster with the nearest mean.

The algorithm attempts to create homogeneous subcategories by minimizing the sum of the squared Euclidean distance between data points in a specific cluster. As such, an interesting feature of k-means clustering is that the distance between individual clusters is as geometrically distant as possible in order to reinforce potential distinctions between the cluster's observations.

Additionally, the K-means algorithm's is particularly effective when clusters are spherical which is often the case with geospatial datasets. Its numerous applications in gleaning insights on location-based data as well as its demonstrated industry track record are the reasons why it has been selected to further illuminate our dataset.

In [76]:
# finding the best k
from sklearn import metrics
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist

la_kmeans = la_grouped_mean_rent.drop(columns = ['Neighborhood']) # drop categorical column
X = la_kmeans.values[:,1:] # define individual arrays
X = np.nan_to_num(X)
la_elbow = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X) # use StandardScaler to reshape and normalize
In [77]:
distortions = [] # create list "distortions"
mapping1 = {} # define mapping

K = range(1, 10) # establish k range
 
for k in K:
    # build and fit the model
    kmeanModel = KMeans(n_clusters=k).fit(la_elbow)
    kmeanModel.fit(la_elbow)
 
    distortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(la_elbow, kmeanModel.cluster_centers_,
                                        'euclidean'), axis=1)) / la_elbow.shape[0])
 
    mapping1[k] = sum(np.min(cdist(la_elbow, kmeanModel.cluster_centers_,
                                   'euclidean'), axis=1)) / la_elbow.shape[0]

Visualize Optimal Value K¶

With the k-means algorithm, the k value is sometimes arbitrarily assigned to a certain value (usually 5 similar to our previous labs). It is, however, better to use the "Elbow Method" to determine the optimal k value in a certain range, which we will do below.

In [78]:
# plot the optimal k using the Elbow Method
plt.plot(K, distortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('Values of K')
plt.ylabel('Distortion')
plt.title('The Elbow Method with Distortion')
plt.show()

The optimal value using distortion occurs when the "elbow" stops decreasing at a linear rate and takes place in our range between 5 and 6 therefore we will assign a kcluster value of 5.

Results:¶

The K-Means Clustering Algorithm produced 5 different clusters that we can analyze visually and through the tabular data presented above.

Cluster 1: This is by far the largest and most geographically pervasive of the 5 clusters (indicated in red), featuring 62 of the total neighborhoods. Monthly average rents range from as low as USD 1403 in Jefferson Park to 4123 in University Park though the vast majority of neighborhoods tend toward the average of 2366 and remain relatively affordable (for LA). In terms of the venues, restaurants, cafes, and coffee shops appear to feature heavily (17 combined instances) with fewer venues for outdoor recreation like parks or trails. Geographically, these neighborhoods appear to be distributed throughout many parts of the sprawling city, including Downtown LA, Santa Monica, Inglewood, the San Fernando Valley and along Route 101. There appears to be quite a bit of demand for coffee shops in some of these neighborhoods.

Cluster 2: Arleta (indicated in purple) is the only neighborhood in this cluster and, for many reasons, appears very distinct from the first cluster. Its rent is well below average at USD 1708 per month and its top 5 featured venues do not include any coffee shops or cafes, rather, movie theaters, historic sites and beach bars constitute the top 3 venue types. It is located out in the San Fernando Valley which is relatively far away from downtown and does not appear to be a likely location to open our next artisanal coffee shop.

Cluster 3: This cluster (indicated in blue) is our second-largest with 18 neighborhoods. Monthly average rents are in a slightly more narrow range than that of Cluster 1, from USD 3703 in Exposition Park to 1423 in Vermont Vista. Coffee shops or cafes feature in the top 5 venues for 5 of the 18 neighborhoods, though it seems restaurants, clothing shops, and fitness venues feature more prominently here. Most neighborhoods tend to be located around the Hollywood, West Hollywood, and Beverly Hills areas with smaller distributions nearby Inglewood and Glendale, making this cluster a prospect for our coffee shop.

Cluster 4: This is our third-largest cluster (indicated in seagreen) with 8 neighborhoods and rents in a far more modest range from USD 2402 in Hollywood to as low as 1533 in Leimert Park. Restaurants, trails, cafes and coffee shops appear frequently in this cluster with 4 instances in the top 5 venues. Geographically, most neighborhoods seem to be centered in and around Hollywood with one major outlier, Leimert Park located in the northwest nearby Van Nuys Airport. Entertainment and dining appear to be more sought-after here and as such, there is some decent potential for craft coffee shops in this cluster.

Cluster 5: Our last cluster contains only 1 neighborhood, Chesterfield Square, (indicated in orange) with an average monthly rent well below average at USD 1809. The top venues for this neighborhood are hardware stores, followed by a variety of different types of restaurants. Geographically, it is actually located nearby neighborhoods from both Clusters 1 (Hyde and Harvard Park) and 3 (Manchester Square). It is different in that it is a primarily commercial area, with a "Foods 4 Less" grocery store in the vicinity, and an unlikely candidate for our coffee shop.

Discussion:¶

The first observations to note derive from a combination of our exploratory data analysis and modeling. In our EDA, we determined which neighborhoods had high numbers of cafes or coffee shops. Of these results we selected 3, Hollywood, Beverly Grove and Koreatown. Unsurprisingly, none of these neighborhoods featured in Cluster 1 which contained the highest number of neighborhoods along with the highest average monthly rents. This outcome was not unexpected as we learned in our correlogram scatterplot that there was very little correlation between the incidence of coffee shops or cafes in neighborhoods with higher rents.

In contrast, it is interesting to note that both Hollywood and Koreatown were clustered together in Cluster 4 which featured neighborhoods with generally below average rent, geographically concentrated across the Hollywood area ranging from Santa Monica in the West all the way to Glendale in the East. As for Beverly Grove, it was clustered in Cluster 3 with a very expensive monthly rental average of 3642, only second after Exposition Park in this grouping.

Coffee Shops and cafes almost always tend to be most frequent in neighborhoods with high numbers of dine-in restaurants such as French and Mexican Restaurants. Furthermore, they do not necessarily operate in places where the rent is most expensive. We cannot ignore the fact that a cup of coffee at a craft coffee shop tends to cost more than the average cup in the US (nearly 41% more in 2019 according to MarketWatch). Therefore it is difficult to be completely "rent-agnostic" when it comes to recommending the best neighborhoods. As such, neighborhoods that feature in both the 3rd and 4th clusters including Beverly Grove, Century City, the Pacific Palisades, Hollywood, Koreatown and Los Feliz are our best recommendations. While the residential rents in these areas are sometimes on the high-end, the type of customer likely to frequent them is also likely to be able to afford the premium charged.

Conclusion:¶

In today's world, there is a constant demand for entrepreneurs and investors to make swift, yet deliberate decisions. With advances in statistical analysis and machine learning algorithms, the process of making these decisions has often become more reliable and data-driven.

The overall objective of this report is to determine potential neighborhoods to open LA's next artisanal coffee shop. To achieve this goal, we scraped data from several sources, wrangled it to produce visualizations and statistical insights and finally applied our K-means algorithm to extract a more intuitive understanding of our data.

There are several notable limitations of this report. Firstly, further data in the form of features such as consumer income such as purchasing power parity (PPP), violent crime data, the use of additional venue / mapping APIs such as the Google Maps or PositionStack APIs could provide more comprehensive information about specific coffee shop names e.g. Starbucks and their respective locations. Additionally, aggregating more average monthly rental data from different sources would allow us to include more neighborhoods in our clustering algorithm, potentially yielding more robust results. Specific data about the cost of commercial rents, local labor laws, taxes, and venue proximities to public transport such as subway or bus stations could very well augment the accuracy or our recommendations.

Despite these limitations, the methodology used and results produced have still generated powerful insights that help to narrow down a process that some might feel is akin to finding a needle in a haystack!
